in the Ghetto, this alliance also serves as a means for black clergy to reaffirm their political leadership and reposition moral authority in black civil society. Drawing on both survey data and fieldwork in New York City, Owens reveals that African American churches can use these newly forged connections with public agencies to influence policy and government responsiveness in a way that reaches beyond traditional electoral or protest politics. The churches and neighborhoods, Owens argues, can see a real benefit from that influence—but it may come at the expense of less involvement at the grassroots. Anyone with a stake in the changing strategies employed by churches as they fight for social justice will find God and Government in the Ghetto compelling reading.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAfrican American churches. 0aChurch and statezUnited States. 0aCommunity development, UrbanzUnited States. 0aFaith-based human servicesxUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  achurch and state, religion, politics, history, spirituality, government, collaboration, race, welfare, grants, poverty, neighborhood, faith, community, clergy, leadership, morality, authority, faith-based organizations, activism, outreach, service, african american, policy, protest, influence, social change, aid, assistance, funding, urban, decline, resources, nonfiction, christianity, baptist, political science, democracy.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311063872108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022664206240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226642086423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226642086/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of C